words.meaning: A prolonged period of abnormally low rainfall, leading to a shortage of water.
examples: The long drought devastated the crops.
The region is suffering from a severe drought.

words.meaning: Hard, menial, or dull work.
examples: He hated the drudgery of his nine-to-five job.
The invention of the washing machine saved people from the drudgery of washing clothes by hand.

words.meaning: Hesitating or doubting; not to be relied upon; suspect.
examples: I was dubious about his chances of success.
He made the dubious claim that he could predict the future.

words.meaning: A feeling of deep resentment or anger.
examples: He stormed out of the room in a fit of dudgeon.
She was in high dudgeon after being insulted.

words.meaning: (Especially of sound) sweet and soothing.
examples: The dulcet tones of the cello filled the room.
She spoke in a dulcet voice that calmed the crying child.

words.meaning: To deceive; to trick.
examples: The con artist managed to dupe the elderly couple out of their life savings.
He was duped into believing a false story.

words.meaning: Deceitful.
examples: He was a duplicitous politician who made promises he never intended to keep.
Her duplicitous behavior eventually led to her downfall.

words.meaning: Deceitfulness; double-dealing.
examples: He was accused of duplicity and fraud.
Her duplicity was exposed when her lies were discovered.

words.meaning: Threats, violence, constraints, or other action brought to bear on someone to do something against their will or better judgment.
examples: He signed the confession under duress.
She claimed she had been acting under duress.

words.meaning: To cause to seem small or insignificant in comparison.
examples: The new skyscraper will dwarf all the other buildings in the city.
His achievements were dwarfed by those of his famous father.

words.meaning: To diminish gradually in size, amount, or strength.
examples: Their savings began to dwindle after he lost his job.
The audience dwindled as the boring lecture continued.

words.meaning: Gradually diminishing in size, amount, or strength.
examples: The dwindling resources became a major concern.
The team had a dwindling number of players due to injuries.

words.meaning: Unchanging in a particular belief or opinion; inveterate.
examples: He is a dyed-in-the-wool conservative who will never change his views.
She is a dyed-in-the-wool fan of the team, supporting them through good times and bad.

words.meaning: A machine for converting mechanical energy into electrical energy; a generator. An extremely energetic person.
examples: The old factory was powered by a massive dynamo.
The new CEO is a real dynamo, full of energy and new ideas.

words.meaning: Of or having indigestion or consequent irritability or depression.
examples: The dyspeptic old man was always complaining about his health.
He had a dyspeptic and gloomy outlook on life.

words.meaning: For example (from the Latin 'exempli gratia').
examples: You can buy many types of citrus fruit, e.g., oranges, lemons, and grapefruits.
Some birds, e.g., the penguin, cannot fly.

words.meaning: Resulting from or showing sincere and intense conviction.
examples: He made an earnest plea for help.
She was an earnest and hardworking student.

words.meaning: The quality of being cheerful and full of energy; exuberance.
examples: The crowd's ebullience was contagious.
She was known for her youthful ebullience and optimism.

words.meaning: Cheerful and full of energy.
examples: She was in an ebullient mood after her team won the championship.
He was an ebullient and enthusiastic tour guide.

words.meaning: (Of a person or their behavior) unconventional and slightly strange.
examples: The eccentric old woman lived in a house full of cats.
He had an eccentric habit of wearing mismatched socks.

words.meaning: A level or rank in an organization, a profession, or society.
examples: The decision was made at the highest echelon of the company.
She had reached the upper echelon of the legal profession.

words.meaning: Deriving ideas, style, or taste from a broad and diverse range of sources.
examples: Her taste in music is eclectic, ranging from classical to hip-hop.
The restaurant has an eclectic menu with dishes from around the world.

words.meaning: To obscure or block out (light); to deprive (someone or something) of significance, power, or prominence.
examples: The moon will eclipse the sun during the solar eclipse.
Her brilliant performance eclipsed that of all the other actors.

words.meaning: Giving good value or service in relation to the amount of money, time, or effort spent.
examples: It is more economical to buy in bulk.
She is an economical shopper who always looks for bargains.

words.meaning: The wealth and resources of a country or region, especially in terms of the production and consumption of goods and services.
examples: The country's economy is growing rapidly.
The global economy is facing a period of uncertainty.

words.meaning: A large, imposing building.
examples: The city hall is a magnificent edifice.
The ancient cathedral is a towering edifice.

words.meaning: To instruct or improve (someone) morally or intellectually.
examples: The teacher's goal was to edify her students, not just to entertain them.
The book was both entertaining and edifying.

words.meaning: Providing moral or intellectual instruction.
examples: It was an edifying documentary that taught me a lot.
She found the lecture to be an edifying experience.

words.meaning: To erase (a mark) from a surface; to make oneself appear insignificant or inconspicuous.
examples: Time had effaced the inscriptions on the gravestone.
She tried to efface herself in the crowd.

words.meaning: Past tense of efface; erased or made inconspicuous.
examples: The memories of that day were slowly effaced by time.
He effaced himself from the family photos.

words.meaning: Bubbles in a liquid; fizz. Vivacity and enthusiasm.
examples: The effervescence of the champagne tickled his nose.
She had a natural effervescence that made her popular.

words.meaning: (Of a liquid) giving off bubbles; fizzy. Vivacious and enthusiastic.
examples: She has an effervescent personality.
The effervescent drink was refreshing on a hot day.

words.meaning: (Of a person) affected, overrefined, and ineffectual; no longer capable of effective action.
examples: The effete aristocracy was out of touch with the common people.
The ancient civilization had become effete and decadent.

words.meaning: (Of something inanimate or abstract) successful in producing a desired or intended result; effective.
examples: The new medicine proved to be highly efficacious in treating the disease.
The most efficacious way to solve the problem is to address the root cause.

words.meaning: The ability to produce a desired or intended result.
examples: The efficacy of the new drug has not yet been proven.
He doubted the efficacy of the government's new policy.

words.meaning: A sculpture or model of a person.
examples: The protesters burned an effigy of the dictator.
The tomb was decorated with the effigy of a knight.

words.meaning: The state or a period of flowering; the highest point of development.
examples: The Renaissance was a period of great artistic efflorescence.
The garden was a beautiful sight during its spring efflorescence.

words.meaning: An unpleasant or harmful odor, secretion, or discharge.
examples: The effluvia from the factory polluted the river.
The room was filled with the effluvia of stale smoke.

words.meaning: Singular of effluvia; an unpleasant or harmful odor, secretion, or discharge.
examples: An unpleasant effluvium was emanating from the swamp.
The chemical plant released a toxic effluvium into the air.

words.meaning: Insolent or impertinent behavior.
examples: He had the effrontery to ask for a raise after only being there for a week.
She was shocked by his effrontery.

words.meaning: Expressing feelings of gratitude, pleasure, or approval in an unrestrained or heartfelt manner.
examples: She was effusive in her praise for the new restaurant.
He gave her an effusive welcome.

words.meaning: Believing in or based on the principle that all people are equal and deserve equal rights and opportunities.
examples: The country is founded on egalitarian principles.
She is a strong advocate for an egalitarian society.

words.meaning: An ethical theory that treats self-interest as the foundation of morality.
examples: His philosophy was based on a form of rational egoism.
The novel explores the conflict between egoism and altruism.

words.meaning: A person who is excessively conceited or absorbed in themselves; a self-seeker.
examples: He is a complete egotist who only cares about himself.
The egotist couldn't stop talking about his own accomplishments.

words.meaning: Excessively conceited or absorbed in oneself; self-centered.
examples: His egotistical behavior alienated many of his friends.
She was tired of his egotistical and boastful stories.

words.meaning: Outstandingly bad; shocking.
examples: It was an egregious error of judgment.
The company was found guilty of egregious violations of safety regulations.

words.meaning: The action of going out of or leaving a place.
examples: The emergency egress was blocked by a pile of boxes.
The contract specifies the terms of egress from the agreement.

words.meaning: To manage to make a living or a supplement to one's income with difficulty.
examples: He had to eke out a living on a small pension.
She eked out a meager existence by selling crafts.

words.meaning: To develop or present (a theory, policy, or system) in detail.
examples: Could you elaborate on your proposal?
He refused to elaborate on his reasons for resigning.

words.meaning: (Of time) to pass or go by.
examples: Several months elapsed before he received a reply.
The deadline has already elapsed.

words.meaning: Ecstatically happy.
examples: She was elated to hear that she had won the award.
The team was elated by their victory.

words.meaning: Weird and sinister or ghostly.
examples: The old house had an eldritch atmosphere that sent shivers down my spine.
He heard an eldritch scream from the abandoned mansion.

words.meaning: (Especially of a work of art) having a mournful quality.
examples: The poem has an elegiac tone, lamenting the loss of a loved one.
The film's elegiac music perfectly captured the mood of the story.

words.meaning: A poem of serious reflection, typically a lament for the dead.
examples: He wrote an elegy for his deceased friend.
The elegy was a moving tribute to the fallen soldiers.

words.meaning: Relating to the basic elements of a subject; straightforward and uncomplicated.
examples: The solution to the problem was elementary.
He was teaching an elementary course in mathematics.

words.meaning: To raise or lift (something) up to a higher position.
examples: The new bridge will elevate the road above the flood plain.
The promotion will elevate her to a position of greater responsibility.

words.meaning: To evoke or draw out (a response, answer, or fact) from someone in reaction to one's own actions or questions.
examples: The lawyer tried to elicit a confession from the witness.
Her comments were intended to elicit a response from the audience.

words.meaning: Relating to or supporting the view that a society or system should be led by an elite.
examples: The country club was criticized for its elitist admission policies.
He had an elitist attitude and looked down on people who were not as wealthy as he was.

words.meaning: A magical or medicinal potion.
examples: The alchemist claimed to have created an elixir of life.
For the weary traveler, the cool water was like an elixir.

words.meaning: Fluent or persuasive speaking or writing.
examples: The politician was known for his eloquence and charisma.
She spoke with great eloquence about the importance of education.
